                <h2>Why Your 'High-CTR' Creatives Aren't Making Money</h2>
<p>The most common complaint among Meta advertisers: "My creative has a great CTR, but CPA is terrible."</p>
<p>The reason is simple: <strong>creatives that can 'run'</strong> (high impressions, high clicks) and <strong>creatives that can 'sell'</strong> (high conversions, high ROI) require two completely different optimization approaches. Mixing them up during review leads to endlessly replicating "high-running" creatives while wondering why sales aren't happening.</p>
<p>The checklist below helps you quickly identify whether a creative can run or sell during your Meta ad review.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Checklist 1: Is the Creative "Running"?</h2>
<p>"Running" means the creative gets recommended by Meta's algorithm and has strong delivery. Check these indicators:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Check Item</th>
<th>Target</th>
<th>Where to Find</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR exceeds industry average by 30%+</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>Ad Set Level → Audience</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPM within reasonable range</td>
<td>&lt; $15 (varies by category)</td>
<td>Campaign Budget → Impressions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Frequency &lt; 3 per user/week</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>Delivery Report → Frequency</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Stable data after 48+ hours</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>Time Dimension</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Creative freshness (&lt; 7 days old)</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>Asset Library Status</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>If all 5 pass → The creative qualifies as "runnable."</strong></p>
<hr />
<h2>Checklist 2: Is the Creative "Selling"?</h2>
<p>"Selling" means the creative drives users to complete the target action (add to cart, sign up, purchase). Check these indicators:</p>
<h3>Conversion Metrics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>CVR (Conversion Rate)</strong>: Add-to-cart &gt; 5%, Checkout &gt; 2% (e-commerce)</li>
<li><strong>CPA (Cost per Action)</strong>: Below 1/3 of LTV</li>
<li><strong>7-Day ROAS</strong> (via Pixel): &gt; 1.5 (ramp-up), &gt; 3.0 (stable)</li>
</ul>
<h3>User Quality Metrics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Page Dwell Time</strong>: Below 10 seconds indicates mismatch between ad and landing page</li>
<li><strong>Bounce Rate</strong>: Above 70% means hook works but value proposition doesn't</li>
<li><strong>Cart Abandonment Rate</strong>: Above 60% signals pricing or trust issues</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>If both CVR and ROAS hit targets → The creative is "selling."</strong></p>
<hr />
<h2>Checklist 3: 3-Step Review SOP</h2>
<p>When analyzing creative data, follow these steps:</p>
<h3>Step 1: Check ROAS First, Then CTR</h3>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Wrong approach</strong>: See 8% CTR, declare creative excellent, replicate blindly.<br />
<strong>Right approach</strong>: Confirm ROAS is profitable first, then analyze whether high CTR comes from a "good hook" or "wrong audience."</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Step 2: Break Down the Conversion Funnel</h3>
<pre><code>Impression → Click → Landing → Add to Cart → Purchase
  ↑         ↑        ↑         ↑
  Where's the biggest drop?
</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>High impressions, low clicks → Hook isn't compelling (optimize thumbnail/first 3 seconds)</li>
<li>High clicks, low landing → Creative and page misaligned (check copy consistency)</li>
<li>High landing, low add-to-cart → Price or USP not prominent (optimize promo info)</li>
<li>High add-to-cart, low purchase → Insufficient trust signals or payment friction</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Compare "Same Group, Different Fate" Creatives</h3>
<p>Place the best and worst performing creatives from the same ad set side by side:<br />
- What's different in color/composition?<br />
- What changed in copy structure?<br />
- Does CTA button placement affect clicks?</p>
<p>One utility app discovered that creatives with a "progress bar" visual element converted at checkout 40% higher than versions listing features only. That's the value of comparative analysis.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Two Common Mistakes</h2>
<h3>Mistake 1: High CTR = Great Creative</h3>
<p>High CTR could come from trending topics, clickbait, or overly broad audience targeting that attracts non-target users. <strong>Running doesn't equal selling.</strong></p>
<h3>Mistake 2: Focusing Only on CPA, Ignoring User Quality</h3>
<p>Sometimes CPA hits the target, but repeat purchase rate is 0. If users buy once and never return, the fundamental issue is creative targeting.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Next Steps</h2>
<p>Create a "Creative Review Sheet" in your Yiyu dashboard and complete the following for each review:</p>
<ol>
<li>Check all 5 items in Checklist 1</li>
<li>Record core metrics from Checklist 2</li>
<li>Identify which funnel stage has the drop-off</li>
<li>Tag the creative as "runnable," "sellable," "dual," or "dead"</li>
</ol>
<p>After two weeks, you'll notice a clear shift in creative optimization: moving from "pursuing clicks" to "pursuing conversions."</p>
